        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana' size='2'> Personally, I think our pets should all be immune to fear, not just the spectre.  After all, what can a freshly arisen mindless corpse really be afraid of?  That is kind of off the point though.</P><P>Being these resists will severely gimp mage pets, I am all for it.  Shammy epic is WAY too easy.  No drops of theirs are rare, all epic mobs are triggered, etc...  This is not about shammies though.  Necro pets should gain some benefit from their owners resists.  Was a joke, mages calm down.</P><P>I think the fairest way to do this would be an either or standpoint.  You summon a pet, your pet gets either 75% (pet is supposed to be weaker than you) of your resistance registered to it or (in the case of mage pets) the current immunity, whichever is higher.  In this instance, the mage pets retain their usefullness in certain situations, and other pets gain a boost to make them have some sort of levelling off point.  To an extent, mage pets gain some benefit too as their pets gain the ability to resist some other types of spells (not all pulls in a high end raid result in only one creature to fight at a time).  Since the pet is still weaker, you will see less resists in with this system, but more partials, which can make some difference depending upon the encounter.  I have actually tried to see some downtime to this system, but have not.  </P><P>Personally I feel this would be fair, and if anyone has some idea on how to modify this system, please post it.  We may catch verant's ear and be able to use this as a startingpoint for an IRC on caster balancing.</P><P>Mommies sad cause the kinky people in the white coats who like to zap me can't catch me.</font></td>
